summary: My Weavile has taken a liking to my neighbor's Lucario and my neighbor has agreed to let them breed. She said that I can adopt...
question: My Weavile has taken a liking to my neighbor's Lucario and my neighbor has agreed to let them breed. She said that I can adopt one of the Riolu if I wanted to. I'm tempted to take her up on that offer. Is there anything important I need to know on how to take care of a Riolu?
answer:
The Riolu family is omnivorous. Nuts and berries make up a large part of their diet, while small mammals and fish make up the rest. Trained individuals usually prefer their meat cooked. Sweet Hearts can be given occasionally as treats.

Not only are Riolu able to understand human speech, they can interpret and inner thoughts and emotions as well. They spend a lot of time training in solitude. When they train, they should not be disturbed. However, outside of practice they can be very affectionate Pokémon. Riolu get stressed when around negative auras. They can detect hostile beings well before they come near, and may behave rather timidly.

I hope this information helps you understand Riolu a little better. Good luck!

summary: oh i forgot to mention in the last message! i have a mimikyu partner pokemon. i hope they wont have anything wrong getting...
question: oh i forgot to mention in the last message! i have a mimikyu partner pokemon. i hope they wont have anything wrong getting along. -connor
answer:
Does your Mimikyu have any scratches? Is anything in your home broken? It’s possible that they may have had a fight while you were asleep.

Doublade may have also drained some life energy from you, which might explain why you most likely wouldn’t wake up from any noise.

If that’s the case, I suggest catching Doublade and releasing it at the nearest Pokémon Center.
